,Not Recommended,320340,20740751,"Posted: 24 January, 2016",all,NihlusGreen,"I wanted to like this title more than I did, what with its elements of management, space, trading and designing your own vessel layout in ant farm view, it ticked a lot of boxes to my liking. Even the characters and art style look fine.But its the mechanics that let this game down.Combat is not up to scratch as quite often you run out of ammo before doing to much damage to your opponent. A prolonged fight results in running out of ammo and then paying a ransom for your surrender. Then head to a shipyard for expensive repairs (~20k). Taking into account vessel combat requirements with rooms dedicate to ammo storage, turrets, torpedo bay etc, while also employing 3-4 specialised crew to man these stations costs money. A lot of money. At the end of the day just focus on cargo and passengers and if a fight arises, just call the aggressor and pay a ransom, its much cheaper ($600-$2500) than all the above requirements.Crew members can go on strike if their needs are not met. What are their needs? Whos knows, clicking on the profile of a striker reveals no negative information, though occasionaly before strike you may see some negative effect which, more often than not, is getting a bee in their bonnet due to another crew mate having a different food preference. Seriously! The more they are levelled up the crazier they get.The tutorial is inadequate with the trading section been the end of it and from memory finishes with ""you have 14 days to do some trading"". Thats not a tutorial, and by the time you get up to some combat, your paying for a lot of trial and error.The game crashes quite reguarly, once or twice every hour with a runtime error, thats apparently wide spread.Jobs given out from spacestations quite often require sourcing and delivery of 30x of X resource, however there is very rarely enough of that resource in the whole system to suffice the job.Sometimes smuggling jobs start from A and involve collecting contraband from planets B and C to deliver to D. Quite often you will run out of time or even with sufficient cargo space it just wont get loaded or more gets loaded than the job specified and when you get to location D, it won't unload, resulting, after a time period, a failed job with a large penalty for you.It would be nice if you could go back to an earlier save to prevent the wasting of big $$$ but Cosmo employs an auto save feature that saves over your older save. No going back = lots of time wasted.Pretty soon it becomes a big boring grind.I truly hope developers Chasing Carrots deliver something greater next time, but as it is Cosmonautica feels like its missing some essential pieces and now its 6 months post release it'll probably stay that way."
