76561198040497624,Not Recommended,320340,31959450,Posted: 25 May,all,็,"My expectations were so high for this game. I love trading games. And I love space and astronomy. I spent a lot of time on Port Royale, Port Royale 2, The Patrician series and when I saw this game I bought it on both Steam and Google Play Store without thinking twice. Just like the games mentioned before you control indirectly, in real time, your spaceship mainly from a top-down view while trading goods from a planet to another. There is a story mode, which I never played, and a sandbox mode, my favourite. A note wich is very important to me: every time you start a new game the entire map is created from the start. You can accept missions at any bar of any planet. You can recruit and manage the crew and every person, or alien, have different skills and traits from combat skill, cook skill, research skill and so on wich you can upgrade. You can customize different models of spaceships from the looks to the position of the rooms inside, pretty much like FTL and you can actually look inside your ship during travels, you are able to see how your ship looks inside and what the crew is doing at that very moment. You can engage pirates and other civillian in combat. You can research new rooms and ways to travel far and explore the galaxy. The overall game look is very pleasant. One major problem affects the entire game: repetitiveness. You do the same thing over and over again. From the missions to the trading. You buy something on a planet and then go sell that thing on another one. You accept the misison here, you go there and finish the mission. The combat doesn't help the situation because is tedious and slow and there are some glitches here and there that mines the game.Unfortunately the game has been abandoned because, according to Chasing Carrots the engine which the game was built with is not so easy to use. I understand the resources for an indie team are scarce, infact this game relfects what happens when you try to make something too big for you to handle. In the end the gamers paid the consequenses.I hope one day the guys at Chasing Carrots, whether by their own work or not, will exhume this game and make what it was supposed to be. Until then, thumb down.The soundtrack is pretty fu**ing great though."
