76561198129101111,Recommended,320340,14643962,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,unknown.notregistered,"EDITED:Released a bit early in my opinion; but it is worth the reasonable pricetag it has. The core is a fancy space trading simulator, with piracy and minimissions tossed in a relatively randomized galaxy. Not completely horrible, but not spectacular either.It still holds some glitches and errors in it - things that should be patched up. But despite that, at its core is a reasonable game for the price.Edit;So you probably want to know more about it - well, its a space sim game. You are a captain of a spaceship and need to decide how to make the most of your ship and crew to get better in the world. And better ships, more monety and all that usual stuff. The tutorial is done well, giving you a purpose and trying to explain how to get further out and explore. But it doesn't hold your hand, you need to at least understand the basics of the ""buy low and sell high"" trading dynamic for the basic profits. Sandbox fits the description with no requirements but your own, and the campaign is not yet done.The gameplay is set very similar to the Sim Tower style of placing rooms inside a ship for the crew needs, then hiring your choice of crew for tasks. You can set the tasks and leisure times of the crew and need to balance it all to run effectively. Don't waste crew overlapping a task when you only need one piloting at a time or cramming the bunk beds cause you didn't realize everyone's off-duty at the same time. So it has some management and planning, but its not quite like the more modern Sims - you don't command the crew directly. Just have them do their tasks and slot the timing. Then watch. The main game is the trading and travel, with the extras on the side.Crew can level up and get better, but the higher levels also mean more needs and demands, and its up to you to supply that for the voyage. You can mitigate some of it by shore leave by staying at stations for a day before a trip, but they may get stressed out on longer trips if you don't have appropriate facilities on board. And that's back to the ship planning and room layout, much like the older Sim Tower as I said. If you ever played that game enough, you'll get this easy. Took me a bitto figure out the staying at a station part, but that was really helpful once I got it - just speed up the ""time"" while docked. You pay the crew for sitting still, but they get relaxed for it better than you usually can on a trip with the ship.Ship travel is selected by you, but the speed is all determined by the pilot skills, if you have a pilot for all 4 shifts, the ship goes faster. But not all skills like that need to be so extensive, and you'll find yourself shuffling the crew roster over time for the right mix of skills as it kind of becomes a test vs the RNG to get the right mix together. Each crewmember also has needs and specials, and you'll find yourself constantly rethinking which crew you have as you may end up with needs you don't want - and overeater can kill your plans for having the cook on board, and a sporty one that needs a fitness room you can't place well can be annoying. But that's back to the shore leave for a solution sometimes, and you'll make do.The primary game is mainly trading, buy low and sell high. You can also become an exclusive transport for passengers or piracy in it, but the game needs some balance between it all for it to work out better. Piracy doesn't pay nearly as well as trading, and passengers can work out but needs some tweaking for the delivery time and rewards to really pay off for the investment. And not all tasks can be done well. Certain crew mixed and ship designes just can't accommodate certain ammounts of passenggers, and the combat is something else...The space travel around the stars are split between 3 rings. The Inner set is the safe zone - no piracy, short trips and easy to get to locations. The Middle has a chance of piracy towards the outter edge, but not frequent. It has longer travels and really requires the ship to start running effectively. The Outer is the hardest. It can have some of the most lucrative trading options out there, but its the hardest to get through with the Piracy almost guarenteed.To gain acess to the rings you need to research it, another crew task, with another room requirement. It can also be used to research other stars to travel to for even more ring research for travel. There is other options for ship and room research, but not implemented as of this writing.Space combat is diferent than you'd expect. You command when the ship fires and activates its short-lived powers availible through certain rooms like hacking or shields. The movement is automatic tho, so its pretty fluid. Damage at this stage in Alpha doesn't mean its a doomed ship when your hull is 0, instead its more work for repair crews and strain for the trip. That and an opposing ship doesn't surrrender to a crippled ship, tho they will run when their health drops low. Perhaps some balance is needed to finish making the danger more real, without it becoming more troublesome. As it is, you need certain rooms that take up space for combat, and each swhip has certain limitations on how many weapon types it can use and where to place them.All and all, its a very promising game. Could use some polish and perhaps more tweaking here and there - but it does the concept well for how it wants to. Definetly one to watch for the future, especially with the intensive dev involvement here."
,Not Recommended,320340,18274224,"Posted: 1 October, 2015",all,Capz,"Potential spoilers on gameplay mechanics.Fun little game, goes boring fast. Get it in sale if you like the genre 10 hours of garanteed fun.The good:- Graphics, artstyle: Love it.- Vibe: Gives a good space feeling. A lot of travelling, which is real. Audio is good and helps with this.- Ship management: the minimal space in your ship makes it that you almost always have too few spaces to get everything, which encourages you to apply your best and preferred set up.- Challenging curve in the start to get a new ship.The Bad:-limited interactions, animations: It's the bare minimum. This makes travelling, one of the major parts you will be doing, get boring FAST.-Balance: Two huge flaws:- Pirate missions reward the most and it's faster to do the low impact missions: less repair costs and you can do more in one time you need to fight a high difficulty enemy, which means you earn more eventually in less time. BREAKS GAME, makes it boring.- Once you have enough money for a specific level of ship (not spoiling) you will be able to complete the game and progress through. At this point you know you can beat everything, and there will be no need to buy another ship and exploring other worlds does not provide anything.The Ugly:- as mentioned above: many planets and solar systems to explore, but there is no need to find them, except the achievement.- Weird bugs.- fights are limited and sometimes it does not do what you want.So I am mixed, you will have fun but not for long. Buy it if you want 15 hours of play and then change to another type of ship. otherwise NO. Buying in sale is advised."
