76561198088489501,Recommended,320340,12705375,"Posted: 31 October, 2014",all,marbeltoast,"Cosmonautica has the kernal of a good idea about a space trading game laced with pirate fights and bribes buried under a few odd features. For example, the game makes it hard to tell whether you would make a profit from trading missons, as all you have to go on regarding the average price of a trade good (before you buy it, that is) is a red arrow pointing left (which I have since discovered means ""Sell here"") and a green arrow pointing right which means ""Buy here"". The game itself gives no clear indication over which means which, and I had to find this out on my own.Another part that could use some work is the tutorial messages, as some of them pop up at the most random of times and because of this make little sense (for example, my robot parrot AI talking about whether or not I enjoyed my trading mission when I'm in space delivering trade goods.) But the biggest problem with the tutorial messages is there is no-where I can go to read 'em when I need 'em, and a player is left with only their memories of how certain things work and what we are trying to acheive.But the biggest problem I find the game has is the problems I run into midflight.Part of the game's challenge comes in the form of having to feed your crew, and keep your crew clean, and give them somwhere to sleep. But your crew operate on a very strict time-schedule, seperated into four segments when they can be either working a skill they have such as cleaning or repairing or piloting your vessal, jobs that have to be done, or keeping themselves alive and not-so-smelly. A problem with this is, when a scheduled relaxation or work segment ends, they drop whatever they were doing regardless of whether they completed their task and get onto the next one. A little margin for error would be nice, so my alien-pastafari can finish it's shower and not have to cook food stark naked and coated in soap. (but seriosly, if they fail perform their tasks then it becomes a consistant problem and they start skiping work to nap or whatever.)On the topic of these time windows, it would be nice if we had a button that both paused the game and let us re-allocate tasks and such without worrying about whether or not Robby hood in the cargo hold is gonna starve if we don't have a pilot at the wheel to get us to his santuary on time.Now, a lot of my complaints are about what might or might not be intentional features of the game to make it harder. Which is why my last nit-pick is: Why is there no diffiiculty slider? This might be indicative of me being outisde the target market for the game, being worse than some at gaming, but at the end of the day, I bought the game and I'd like to make it further than the first rim. It's wise to either add a diffuculty slider for us less good gamers or make it more obvious that one failed trading mission can drive you to total bankrupcy, and that this game is for people who are gluttons for punishment.You might think after reading all that that I don't like Cosmonautica, but that's just not true. I like it, I just don't know if it likes me. It needs work, yeah, but it could be a great game one day, once it loses it's bumps and blisters."
