,Recommended,320340,18476594,"Posted: 14 October, 2015",all,jay_foxie,"--Initial look--I first found this game on steam after playing 'FTL'(which I got bored of very quickly), then playing 'Space rogue'(which is basically FTL with better graphics but buggy as hell). The pics looked good, adds a trading and exploration element, as well as the ability to change up your ship in ports to suit your needs.All this combined with the fact that it was a steam greenlight game, the reviews were mixed(most of the bad ones just stupid little gripes about things that didn't even effect game play) and is currently $14.99 USD on steam, meant that it was worth the risk to buy and give it a go.--Graphics--At first glance I was disappointed with the graphics.That was until I took a closer look at the way it was done, the creators of Cosmonautica have taken a large attention to tiny little details and overlaid the entire game with a filter that resembles the horizontal lines you used to get with old LCD screens. Which in my opinion gives the game that old sci fi feel, like you're overseeing the play of the game from your own consol on the ship.--In game world--The map is large and unless you're playing in story mode is procedurally generated for that extra replay value. Each solar system map has four rings with a few planets, the starter ring and the next three that you can research to gain access too. Then you have your star chart, you start with one quadrant which usually has three solar systems in it, then you can research further star charts and expand your travels in world.--Game play/Controls--Controls are a simple point and click interface, most things are fairly self explanatory and everything else you just need to click on for a explanation or description.Game play is fun and addictive. You start off with a little ship and some money and have to fit out your ship from the start, choosing either to take a few passengers, a lot of cargo or split the difference. You will need to hire staff based on skills and wages, with added traits which can determine how well your staff actually get along.It all comes down to managing your staffs well being, meeting deadlines(or suffer a penalty) and making money to improve your ship or just buy and fit out a new one. Then latter on when you have researched a little and have enough crew to man weapons of shields you can ship goods into bad zones(careful of customs and their heavy fines), hunt pirates or just become a pirate yourself.--Story--Story mode is fun, you have a slightly psychotic robot parrot as your companion who gives you comical hints on what to do next or just randomly develops red eyes and starts screaming at you, sometimes in command code(and then apologises).--Overall--When I first started playing it had some bugs, but nothing that affected game play, usually just little things like a crew member doing one thing and the character tile saying they are doing another, that being said the developers at Chasing Carrots are at the top of their game and have any bugs fixed really fast.This is a great game and did everything the other games should have done and with a better look, style and with a comical twist(like space ships being modeled after actual ships).If you have played FTL or Space rogue and just got bored of it being the exact same thing over and over and over, give Cosmonautica a try.Again currently on Steam for $14.99 USD, the Apple store for $6.99 and Goggle play for $8.99 USDGraphics: 8/10 For style.In-game world: 9/10Game play: 8/10Story: 7/10Overall Score: 8/10"
