,Recommended,320340,22737284,"Posted: 30 April, 2016",all,SciStarborne,"I grabbed this while it was 50% off since it looked entertaining despite mixed reviews. And it is entertaining, especially at that price. I'd probably be grinding my teeth a bit if I'd paid full for it though.It does suffer from both bugs and unpolished gameplay, but it is still fun to play. It crashes occasionally, but has so far always reloaded quickly with little loss of progress. It even seems to save more often than advertised ""at every station"". So the crashes are irksome but not serious as far as playing it goes.Some more annoying bits are a mission not completing when it detects the tasks out of order, differences between mission requirements and what you actually need for them, and flight paths suddenly changing and making you miss deadlines (particularly on longer ones). They are at least fairly minor though. Not being able to adjust the window size is also a minor annoyance, having it allways about 5 pixels wider than my screen.Also you can sometimes manage the flightpath issue by selecting other destinations when it goes wrong (usually a huge loop out in front of the planets orbit when half way there) to force a course-change, then change back again. It requires some micro-management.Ship and tech progression don't match well and it's very easy to run on with the storyline then realise you've progressed yourself into an unwinable situation. Ship combat also isn't well explained. It does feel like it's missing its final polish.The way you manage your crew however is very nice and creative with the morale system, and when you do upgrade your ship it is fun kitting it out. Building up a ship is rewarding, especially once you start stacking multiple jobs for destinations.So despite its flaws, it's still a fun game. Get it while it's cheap."
