76561197964120751,Recommended,320340,14188308,"Posted: 26 January, 2015",all,Hyperlynx,"Well, it's charming and fun to play, but unfortunately the gameplay still has some kinks in it. This game still needs some love and polish, and iterative playtesting, but since I'm actually enjoying myself playing it I have to recommend it.The good: it's fun to recruit a crew, train them up to be an efficient fighting machine, and travel the cosmos in search of fun and profit. This game gets those basics right. And the presentation is absolutely charming. And the solar systems use simple orbital mechanics! As a Kerbal Space Program player that's pretty damn awesome to see.There are some problems that stop the game short of true greatness. Aside from the storyline missions, the gameplay is rather repetitive. When you've seen one system, you've seen them all, especially if you're a combat vessel rather than a trader. There are only a handful of basic missions, and you see the same ones over and over again.There are also some balance/tuning issues that need to be addressed.For one thing, fighting other vessels produces OUTRAGEOUS profit, far beyond anything else. This is because when you're beating the enemy they hail you to surrender and offer money and cargo to let them live. That money is always much, much higher than any possible mission reward you were getting to fight them. A simple bounty mission might be around 7,500 credits, while the ransom is likely to be 42,000!Trading still doesn't produce much profit unless you go for the higher value goods. That's fine, except that when you sell goods to a station they remain in that station and slowly disappear over time (as the inhabitants use them up, presumably). The problem is that this decay rate is far too slow. You end up stuffing the planet full of goods and unable to sell because everyone is still working their way through the last batch. Basically, you have to sell to planets other than ones that actually have a demand for your goods, and I'm reasonably sure that you could glut a whole system without much trouble.Some of the crew roles simply aren't useful, ditto ship rooms. There's a galley that requires a cook to operate, but the starting food vending machine is more than adequate for a full crew, and by the time you've researched the tech for the galley it's a simple matter to research the upgrade that makes the galley operate without a cook. Since upgrades are done by researching a technology, and that technology is used by different unlocks or upgrades, it's quite easy to inadvertently unlock automating the galley because you unlocked the prereq techs for other benefits they unlock.Same story with medics/medbay - the pill dispenser works just as well, doesn't require training, and the medbay gets automated by upgrades.Crew preferences and interactions is a nice idea in theory but it's simple enough to get crewmates who all like the same food and then you never have to worry about it again.There isn't enough different mission text, so missions will repeat constantly. It's a very minor quibble, but it gets annoying reading the same description over and over and over.Basically, the game isn't balanced. The result is there's no real incentive to do anything other than what is most effective (ie, fight ships for outrageous ransoms). In a way you're punished for taking alternate approaches because they're so dismally ineffective by comparison.It feels like this game has tremendous potential that could be unlocked by gameplay tuning. This would turn it from a ""pretty good"" game to an amazingly fantastic one. That said, it's still a pretty good game, and you should get it.-----------------------------OLD, EARLY ACCESS REVIEW:Charming presentation and shows great promise, but needs more work on gameplay tuning before it's actually fun to play. Cargo trading, for example, produces barely any profit.This has every sign of becoming an excellent game, but it's not there yet, so I can't really recommend it (unless you just want to support them). The issues are easy enough to fix by simple iterative playtesting and balancing, so I don't expect this will stay a problem in the future."
